            "Ammeter",
            "Measures the flow of electrons",
            "Used for current"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "What instrument is required to check the electrical pressure or potential difference between two points?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Voltmeter",
            "Measures electrical pressure",
            "Measures potential difference"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which instrument is used to find the electrical resistance of a component in Ohms?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Ohmmeter",
            "Measures how much a component resists flow",
            "Measures Ohms"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Why is it technically incorrect and potentially dangerous to use the terms 'voltage' and 'current' interchangeably when selecting a measuring instrument?",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "They represent entirely different physical properties",
        "Voltage is electrical pressure while current is electrical flow",
        "Selecting the wrong instrument can result in no reading or incorrect data",
        "Using the wrong meter can cause potential damage to the test equipment"
      ],
      "hint": "Match the name of the unit (Amps, Volts, Ohms) to the name of the meter (Ammeter, Voltmeter, Ohmmeter)."
    },
    {
      "title": "Measuring Power and Energy",
      "basicQuestions": [
        {
          "questionText": "What instrument is used to measure the rate of doing work (power) in Watts at a single moment?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Wattmeter",
            "Measures instantaneous power",
            "Measures the rate of doing work"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which meter is used to track the total electrical energy consumed over a period of time?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Energy Meter",
            "kWh meter",
            "Tracks cumulative usage over hours or days"
          ]
        },
        {
          "questionText": "Which specific meter is used by utility companies to calculate an electricity bill based on total work done?",
          "answerGuidance": [
            "Energy Meter",
            "kWh meter",
            "Used for cumulative consumption tracking"
          ]
        }
      ],
      "deeperQuestionText": "Using the car analogy provided in the lesson, explain why a Wattmeter is insufficient for determining a building's monthly energy consumption.",
      "deeperAnswerGuidance": [
        "A Wattmeter only measures the 'right now' value or instantaneous power",
        "Energy is the total power consumed over a period of time",
        "A Wattmeter is like a speedometer (speed at a moment) whereas energy requires an odometer (total distance)",
        "Billing requires cumulative data which a standard Wattmeter does not provide"
      ],
      "hint": "Think about whether you are measuring a 'right now' value (Power) or a 'total over time' value (Energy)."
    }
  ]
}

{
  "integrative": {
    "title": "Full System Diagnostic Selection",
    "objective": "Evaluate the learner's ability to select the correct measuring instruments for a complete set of electrical parameters in a practical scenario.",
    "retrievalTextLines": [
      "To fully understand an electrical system, we often need to measure multiple quantities. You might need to check the electrical pressure (potential difference), the actual flow of electrons, the physical resistance of the components, the rate at which work is being done right now, and the total work done over a period of time.",
      "Each of these requires a specific, dedicated instrument to ensure accuracy and safety. Mixing these up can lead to incorrect data or damage to your testing equipment."
    ],
    "questionText": "You are performing a full audit of a commercial water heater. You need to measure: 1. The electrical pressure across the terminals. 2. The flow of electricity through the circuit. 3. The resistance of the heating element (while isolated). 4. The instantaneous power demand. 5. The total energy consumed over a 24-hour shift. List the five specific instruments you would use for these measurements in the order they are described.",
    "answerGuidance": [
      "Voltmeter (for electrical pressure/voltage)",
      "Ammeter (for flow/current)",
      "Ohmmeter (for resistance)",
      "Wattmeter (for instantaneous power)",
      "Energy meter or kWh meter (for total energy consumption)"
    ],
    "hint": "Match the meter to the quantity: pressure (Volts), flow (Amps), resistance (Ohms), rate of work (Watts), and total work over time (Energy)."
  }
}

